ğŸ” PtH vs. PtT â€” When to Use Each
Feature	Pass the Hash (PtH)	Pass the Ticket (PtT)
ğŸ” Auth Mechanism	NTLM	Kerberos
ğŸ”‘ Credential Used	NTLM hash (rc4_hmac)	Kerberos ticket (TGT/TGS)
ğŸ§  Knowledge Needed	NTLM hash of user	TGT/TGS or key material
ğŸ–¥ï¸ Typical Use Case	Lateral movement to machines that accept NTLM (e.g., SMB, WMI, RDP)	Lateral movement to machines that require Kerberos-based auth (e.g., AD-integrated apps, constrained delegation scenarios)
ğŸ§± Barriers	May fail if SMB signing is enforced, or NTLM is disabled	May fail if tickets expire or are detected
ğŸ” Detection	High â€” NTLM downgrade, reused hashes	Lower â€” if AES keys are used and ticket lifetimes are respected
ğŸ§  Real-World Scenario Breakdown
ğŸ”“ Use PtH when:
Youâ€™ve dumped NTLM hashes from LSASS or SAM.

You're targeting local admin access over SMB, WMI, or WinRM.

The environment supports NTLM (some modern ones don't!).

E.g. You dump Administrator's NTLM hash from MS01, and use crackmapexec to log into MS02.

ğŸŸï¸ Use PtT when:
You dumped a Kerberos ticket (TGT or TGS).

You got Kerberos keys and want to generate a valid ticket (OverPass the Hash).

You're trying to blend in with normal ticket activity or bypass NTLM restrictions.

You're accessing Kerberos-only services like:

SQL with integrated auth

PSRemoting when NTLM is blocked

Anything requiring SSO where NTLM wonâ€™t cut it

E.g. You phish a user, dump their AES key, then craft a TGT using Rubeus and asktgt /ptt, and connect over PowerShell Remoting.

ğŸ”€ Order of Operations Cheat Sheet
Hereâ€™s a general flow when moving laterally post-compromise:

ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Local Loot
