SMB rejects NTLM	Try accessing over Kerberos using a forged ticket (PtT)
ğŸ”š Bottom Line
PtH is quick-and-dirty, but easily caught and becoming obsolete.

PtT is cleaner, fits better in modern environments, and gives access to more advanced attack paths like delegation abuse and Kerberoasting chaining.

If you can get Kerberos keys or tickets â€” PtT is king. If all you have is a hash â€” PtH is your backup.

ğŸ« Pass-the-Ticket (PtT) + Double Hop Gotcha
âœ… Whatâ€™s the Problem?
When you use Kerberos (PtT) to connect to another box (like via PSRemoting or SMB), your TGT (ticket-granting ticket) is not automatically forwarded to the remote machine.

This is by design â€” it's a security feature of Kerberos to prevent â€œunintended delegationâ€ (a.k.a. Double Hop Attacks).

ğŸ”„ So What Happens?
You PtT into DC01 with user john@domain.

You run Enter-PSSession DC01.

You're now on DC01 but your TGT is still only valid on MS01, where you originally injected it.

Now you try to RDP, PSRemote, or connect to FS01 from DC01... fail âŒ

Because DC01 canâ€™t request another service ticket on your behalf â€” your TGT isnâ€™t there.

ğŸ’¡ Your Fix = Log out â†’ Re-Inject â†’ Enumerate again
ğŸ§­ Workflow:
Inject TGT with PtT (Rubeus ptt or mimikatz kerberos::ptt)

Connect to Target1 (e.g. DC01) via PSRemoting, SMB, RDP

ENUM HARD AF ğŸ’¥ (loot, dump, check sessions, creds, ACLs)

Log out from session (e.g. exit PSRemoting, close RDP, etc.)

Inject TGT or TGS for next target (FS01, SQL01, etc.)

Repeat the process

ğŸ§  Bonus: Kerberos Delegation Paths = Bypass Double Hop (Advanced)
Later you'll see:

Unconstrained Delegation ğŸ§¨

Constrained Delegation (S4U2Self / S4U2Proxy)

Resource-Based Constrained Delegation

These allow a machine or service to impersonate you to another service legally in Kerberos â€” that's how attackers bypass double hop in some advanced chains.

But unless youâ€™re abusing those: â¡ï¸ You gotta bounce between sessions and inject again.

ğŸ”š TL;DR:
ğŸ’¡ Point	âœ… Yes or âŒ No
Can I PtT into DC01 and use that ticket again to reach SQL01 from inside DC01?	âŒ No (unless delegation abuse is possible)
